R1) DeepSeek has completely disrupted the market by offering "reasoning" models that rival GPT-4o but at
1/50th of the cost. * The "Lot": They often give 2–5 million tokens for free to start, and their paid tier is so cheap
($0.20 per 1M tokens) that $5 will last a developer months of high-volume use. * Coding Ability: Their R1 model
uses "Chain-of-Thought" reasoning, meaning it explains its logic before writing the code—essential for complex
architecture. 2. Google AI Studio (Gemini 2.5 Flash) * The "Lot": Up to 1,500 requests per day and a staggering 1
million token context window for free. * Coding Ability: This is the only free API that can "read" your entire
codebase (30,000+ lines) in one go to find a bug or refactor a system. It is the king of "Repo-level"
understanding. 3. Puter.js (Qwen 2.5 Coder / Qwen 3) * The "Lot": Puter provides a "User-Pays" bridge that
currently allows unlimited free access to the Qwen family of models. * Coding Ability: Qwen 2.5 Coder is widely
considered the best open-source coding model. It outperforms Llama in Python and C++ benchmarks and is
highly "agentic" (great at using tools). 4. Mistral AI (Codestral) * The "Lot": Their "Experiment" tier allows for
consistent, free access (approx. 1 request per second). * Coding Ability: Codestral is a specialist model. It was
trained specifically on 80+ programming languages. It excels at "Fill-In-the-Middle" (FIM), which is the logic used
for real-time autocomplete in IDEs like VS Code. 5. Groq (Llama 3.3 70B) * The "Lot": Extremely high Rate Limits
(RPM). It’s not "unlimited tokens," but the frequency of chats allowed is much higher than OpenAI or Anthropic. *
Coding Ability: Speed. Groq is so fast (300+ tokens/sec) that it makes the coding experience feel like a live
conversation. Best for quick boilerplate and unit tests. 6. SiliconFlow * The "Lot": One of the cheapest providers
globally ($0.05–$0.08 per 1M tokens). * Coding Ability: They host DeepSeek-V3 and Qwen-Coder at "full
precision," meaning the model isn't "dumbed down" to save server space. You get the smartest version of the
model for pennies. 7. Blackbox AI * The "Lot": Very aggressive free tier specifically for the coding community. *
Coding Ability: It has a "Real-time Web Search" feature built into the coding API. If you’re using a library that was
updated yesterday, Blackbox can find the new documentation, whereas most LLMs would hallucinate the old
version. 8. Together AI * The "Lot": They provide $25 in free credits upon sign-up. Because their models (like
Llama 4 Scout) are so cheap, $25 can easily cover 10 million+ tokens. * Coding Ability: Huge variety. You can
"hot-swap" between 50 different coding models to see which one handles your specific framework (React, Rust,
etc.) most accurately. 9. OpenRouter (Free Library) * The "Lot": A unified API that aggregates all "Free" models
from other providers into one list. * Coding Ability: It allows you to build a coding agent that never "dies"—if one
free provider goes down, OpenRouter automatically switches you to another free coding model. 10. Cerebras
(Llama 3.1 405B) * The "Lot": High-volume free tier for their "Wafer-Scale" inference. * Coding Ability: It gives
you free access to Llama 405B, the largest open-source model. It has the raw "IQ" to handle high-stakes logic
