Page 1 of 4iFuse (libimobiledevice) can mount your iPhone’s file system and allow you to write files from Linux. The problem?
These files won’t show up anywhere useful on the iPhone – not in the Files app, not in Photos, not in any media
app. Best used for pulling photos/videos OFF the iPhone. KDE Connect (Limited iOS Support) KDE Connect has
made great strides in Linux-to-Android file transfers, but iOS support is a different story. With the official KDE
Connect app from the App Store, you’ll find that file transfers are one-way only, and even then, heavily restricted.
You can pull files from the iPhone to Linux (sometimes), but you can’t push files to the iPhone. Pushcut —
Webhook Bridge Use it for notifying me of events on Linux server, like a site update deployment. There are myriad
possibilities. Your Linux server can trigger iOS shortcuts via HTTP webhooks using Pushcut’s API.
ifuse — Mount iPhone on Linux (USB) Install the ifuse package. You can then run the following command to
mount your iPhone’s media filesystem. You can use this to access the device’s photos inside mountpoint/DCIM.
LocalSend — The AirDrop for Everything LocalSend uses your local WiFi network to transfer files. Your data never
leaves your local network. All transfers are encrypted using HTTPS. LocalSend is available for Windows, macOS,
Linux, Android, and iOS. No account, no login, no servers. The app works as a cross-platform tool for transferring
files between devices, offering functionality similar to Apple’s AirDrop but without being limited to a single
ecosystem. It works across just about every platform out there including Android, iOS, iPad OS, Windows, Mac
and Linux.
Webhook Triggers for Remote Automation Execute an iOS shortcut from a HomeKit automation. Convert your
HomeKit automation into a shortcut and use the Get Contents of URL action to run a ‘real’ shortcut on your iOS
server. Trigger smart notifications from Shortcuts, HomeKit, schedules, locations, iBeacons, online services (like
IFTTT, Zapier, Flow, Integromat), home servers, or anywhere that knows what HTTP is. NFC Tag Automation As a
Shortcuts user I like to automate more stuff to make sure I can switch on or off things in the easiest way possible.
For that, I needed to use NFC tags and connect some additional lights to Apple Home using the app called
Homebridge. Buy cheap NFC stickers, program them to trigger shortcuts when you tap your phone against them.
