iOS 26 Developer Mode — Unlock System Access iOS 26 Developer Mode stands out as the safest and most
flexible way to install IPA files, access developer settings, and customize your iPhone’s system performance. You
can safely sideload apps, test beta builds, and use debugging tools without jailbreaking. To enable: Go to Settings
→ Privacy & Security → Developer Mode, toggle it on, restart your device. Sideloading Methods
AltStore/Sideloadly (Free Apple ID): Apps need re-signing every 7 days, but tools like AltStore can automate
iPhone/Watch Widget: Use a Python script to poll the Home Assistant API.
The iPhone Side (Scriptable) Use the Scriptable app to create custom iOS home screen widgets that show Ubuntu stats. •
The Workflow: Run a simple FastAPI (Python) script on Ubuntu that listens for requests. Scriptable on your iPhone makes a
GET request to your laptop’s IP (via Tailscale) to fetch CPU load, RAM usage, and active Hyprland workspace. 4. The 2026
"OP" Automation Logic • Auto-Lock by Proximity: Set up a script on Ubuntu that pings your iPhone’s IP (via Tailscale). If the
ping latency exceeds 50ms (meaning you walked away), Hyprland triggers hyprlock automatically. • Apple Watch
"Terminal": Use the Blink Shell app on your Watch. In 2026, it supports basic "Trigger" buttons. You can restart a stuck
process on Ubuntu by tapping your wrist. • AirPods Audio-Switch: Use PipeWire's wireplumber on Ubuntu to detect when
your AirPods connect. Have it automatically switch your default output and send a notification to your iPhone saying
"Ubuntu Audio Hijacked."
