1. The Core: Performance & Window Management To make Ubuntu feel "OP," you need to bypass the standard GNOME shell
for Hyprland. • Kernel: Swap the generic kernel for Liquorix or XanMod. • Reason: These are optimized for low-latency
desktop use and will make Hyprland’s animations and window switching feel instantaneous. • Window Manager: Hyprland
(Wayland). • On Ubuntu, don't use the standard repos; use the Hyprland-Ubt automated build scripts (popular in 2026) to
ensure all dependencies are handled. • Status Bar: Waybar. • You’ll use Waybar as your data hub, showing your iPhone and
Apple Watch battery alongside your CPU/GPU vitals. 2. The Connectivity Bridge (The Glue) To get "Full Control," you need
to bridge the Apple-Linux divide using two specific tools: A. KDE Connect (iOS + Linux) This is the single most important
tool for an iPhone-Ubuntu user. • Widgets: You get a "Remote Commands" widget on your iPhone. • Control: Map
commands like hyprctl dispatch exit (Close Hyprland) or systemctl suspend to buttons on your iPhone and Apple Watch. •
Clipboard: Copy a bash script on your Ubuntu terminal, paste it directly into your iPhone notes. B. Home Assistant (Self-
Hosted on Ubuntu) You don't need fancy smart home gear; you are using this to pull Apple Sensors. 1. Install Home
Assistant in a Docker container on your Ubuntu laptop. 2. Install the Home Assistant Companion App on your iPhone and
Watch. 3. The Result: Your iPhone will now send its battery %, Focus Mode (Do Not Disturb), and Apple Watch battery %
directly to your Ubuntu machine via a local API. 3. The Widget Stack: Cross-Device Sync This is what you specifically asked
for—widgets that talk to each other. The Linux Side (Eww + Waybar) Use Eww (Elkowar’s Wacky Widgets) for a "floating"
glass dashboard. AirPods Widget: Use AirStatus (Python CLI). It scans BLE beacons to find your AirPods' charge levels
(Left, Right, Case) and displays them in a clean table or Waybar tooltip.
