1. Focus Mode Sync: When you flip your iPhone 12 to "Work" Focus, Home Assistant detects the state change and sends a
webhook to your Linux machine. Hyprland automatically changes your wallpaper, launches your IDE, and silences
notifications. 2. Watch Triggers: You can create a "Lock Laptop" button on your Apple Watch. Tapping it sends a command
via KDE Connect to execute hyprlock. 3. AirPods Auto-Switch: Use a script that detects when your AirPods MAC address
connects to your phone; it can automatically pause media on Linux or vice-versa using playerctl.
The Widget Stack
This is how you get the cross-device battery and status syncing you requested. A. Linux Desktop Widgets (Eww + Waybar)
Don't just use a bar; use Eww (Elkowar’s Wacky Widgets). It’s written in Rust and allows for highly styled, interactive CSS
widgets. • iPhone/Watch Battery on Linux: Write a simple bash script that curls the Home Assistant API to get your iPhone
12's battery level and outputs it to an Eww widget or a Waybar module. • AirPods Battery: In 2026, use pipewire-airpods-
battery scripts. Since AirPods don't use standard Bluetooth Battery Service, these scripts scan BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy)
beacons to grab the % of each bud and the case. B. iPhone/Watch Widgets (Scriptable) • Tool: Scriptable (iOS App). • The
Setup: Write a JavaScript snippet in Scriptable that polls your Linux laptop's status (CPU temp, RAM, Uptime) via an SSH
command (using Blink Shell integration) or a simple Python http.server. • Result: A native iOS widget on your iPhone 12
home screen showing your Linux laptop's real-time "vitals."
Hyprland
HA 2026 now features Matter 2.0 and Thread native support. It acts as the "Fake HomeKit Bridge" that allows
your Apple Watch to trigger Linux scripts via Siri without ever touching the cloud.
